title: Dangerous winter storm in Midwest causes chaos as 175 crashes reported in 13 hours - Weather - News - Daily Express US
text: Dangerous winter storm in Midwest causes chaos as 175 car crashes reported in 13 hours The Midwest was forecast to see up to six inches of snow on Friday, covering several highways and interstates in the region. New York: Plane skids off snowy runway in Rochester As [a deadly winter storm](/news/weather/132013/winter-storm-warning-snow-forecast-maps-us-weather) makes its way across the Great Lakes on Friday, those traveling on highways in the Midwest are facing dangerous conditions, especially in [Minnesota](/latest/minnesota). Minnesota State Police reported that 175 crashes occurred during a 13-hour period from Thursday night into Friday morning statewide. Nineteen of those crashes involved injuries, and one involved a fatality. A 54-year-old man was killed on Interstate 90 in Manchester Township on Thursday night due to icy conditions, police said. Another 101 vehicles have also spun out on roads, highway police said. The Midwest was forecast to see up to six inches of [snow](/latest/snow) on Friday, covering several highways and interstates in the region. READ MORE: [Winter storm warning - Map shows 17 states on snow alert as up to 18ins to fall](/news/weather/132013/winter-storm-warning-snow-forecast-maps-us-weather) Several more inches of snow are expected to hit southern [Wisconsin](/latest/wisconsin) and central [Michigan](/latest/michigan) throughout the day. Some areas in the region may even see ‚Äúthundersnow,‚Äù with snow rates at one to two inches per hour. FOX Weather Winter Storm Specialist Tom Niziol said: ‚ÄúThe system is so strong in the mid-levels of the atmosphere that we‚Äôre getting thundersnow reported across the area. ‚ÄúThe Storm Prediction Center just put out a discussion referring to the fact that we‚Äôve got a lot of deep convection going on with that thundersnow. That‚Äôs why you‚Äôre going to see these snowfall rates.‚Äù If traveling this morning, many highways in WisDOT's Northwest Region are either snow covered or have slippery stretches. Give yourself extra time to get to your destination and don't forget to buckle up.‚Äî WisDOT Northwest Region (@WisDOTnorthwest) [pic.twitter.com/v9nvjFO3bY] [March 22, 2024] States under winter weather advisories on Friday include Minnesota, Wisconsin, Michigan, and [Iowa](/latest/iowa). While snow is expected to end by Friday night as sub-zero temperatures set in, an even stronger winter storm is forecast for the Midwest early next week. The current storm will move into the Northeast Friday night into Saturday, bringing intense, heavy rain. Winter storm warnings are already in effect across portions of the interior Northeast and northern New England that may see heavy snow from the system. author: Anthony Robledo
title: Viral photo of forlorn Spiral Hot Dogs owner leads to booming business
text: Customer's photo of forlorn owner in empty restaurant leads business to boom at OK diner Nick Chappell had never been to Spirals Hot Dogs & More before he took a photo of Scott Hosek in his empty restaurant. But after business boomed, Chappell's part of the Spirals family, Hosek says. [Anthony Robledo](https://www.usatoday.com/staff/7612431001/anthony-robledo/) An Oklahoma hot dog joint owner visibly wanted customers one day and he soon got more than he bargained for. During a slow shift on Dec. 20, a customer took a photo of Scott Hosek standing by his restaurant entrance waiting for diners and shared it on social media. Hosek would soon have no time to stand around as " [Spirals: Hot Dogs & More](https://spiralshotdogs.com/)," in Norman, Oklahoma, saw booming business once the post went viral. "We immediately started doing double digits in sales," Hosek told USA TODAY on Thursday. "It happened really fast to me." The day the photo was taken, Hosek found himself staring out the window upset his family business of four years wasn't booming as well as others ahead of Christmas. Hosek said he had no idea why Spirals saw a sudden wave of new customers after Dec. 20 until the person responsible for posting the photo, Nick Chappell, later apologized and offered to take the post down. Hosek wouldn't hear of it. "You just wouldn't expect it. Social media is amazing. It's amazing that people get involved with it," he said. "But more importantly, it's the stuff that you just don't think would work. That's what works." 'I will always love you': [See Dolly Parton grant Utah man's dying wish to meet her](https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/life/humankind/2023/12/26/dolly-parton-meets-longtime-fan/72033945007/) Customer knew he had to capture 'wholesome moment' Chappell visited the Norman area for his job as an Oklahoma Army National Guard. As part of their weekly hot dog Wednesday routine, Chappell and a his co-worker found Spirals on Google Maps and took a chance. Noticing Hosek gazing, Chappell decided to capture the "wholesome moment" on Snapchat captioning "He has been standing here waiting on customers to come in." "A good buddy of mine named Chad said, 'Hey, man, you can either post this on Facebook or I'm going to post this on Facebook. Some way or another we're going to get this guy some customers,'" Chappell said. In a Facebook post, Chappell gave an excellent recommendation of the restaurant, complimenting their food and "off the charts" service. He shared a photo of his dish, the menu and of Hosek waiting for diners. Chappell was blown away by the success of the post, which has since had over 2,000 shares, and even more surprised to see over 70 guests at the diner during his next visit. "I'm not a huge social media guy I typically don't share," Chappell said. "I don't even know really the words to describe it as but it made me even that much happier that I did make a post." Owner adds new 'Thunderbird' item in customer's honor Hosek is showing his gratitude by adding a new item in Chappell's honor. Having named hot dogs and bowls after family members, he was more than happy to do so. The "Thunderbird" is a hot link with bacon, cream cheese and jalape√±os, Hosek said. The meal gets its name from the Thunderbird Unit Patch for the 45th Infantry, which Chappell is a part of. The two reconnected at the restaurant on Thursday, where they both got emotional talking about the post's impact. Chappell received a certificate of appreciation during the unveiling of the "Thunderbird" and was told he is now forever part of the Spirals family. "To know that it was a humble guy that just saw our need and did what he could. He doesn‚Äôt have a real following on social media, he hardly ever shares anything and to know that one post had so much power. It was super cool," Hosek added.
